    "abstractNote": "Characteristic of Northwest Semitic languages is the sound change <i>w>y</i> in initial position, e.g. Semitic *<i>wald</i> \u2018child\u2019 > Hebrew <i>y\u00e9led</i>, Syriac <i>yald\u014d</i>. In this article the author defines more accurately, in synchronic perspective, the parameters of this alternation in Classical Syriac and suggests an explanation. The shift is phonologically conditioned: it takes place in initial, postconsonantal and geminate positions. This conditioning and other phonological considerations demonstrate that <i>w>y</i> is a strengthening, a phenomenon which is common in many languages. Evidence is drawn not only from I-w roots but also from II-w roots where the change <i>w>y</i> appears as well.",
